Project: Identify Customer Segments¶

In this project, you will apply unsupervised learning techniques to identify segments of the population that form the core customer base for a mail-order sales company in Germany. These segments can then be used to direct marketing campaigns towards audiences that will have the highest expected rate of returns. The data that you will use has been provided by our partners at Bertelsmann Arvato Analytics, and represents a real-life data science task.

This notebook will help you complete this task by providing a framework within which you will perform your analysis steps. Feel free to add additional code and markdown cells as you go along so that you can explore everything in precise chunks. The code cells provided in the base template will outline only the major tasks, and will usually not be enough to cover all of the minor tasks that comprise it.

Step 0: Load the Data¶

There are four files associated with this project (not including this one):

  • Udacity_AZDIAS_Subset.csv: Demographics data for the general population of Germany; 891211 persons (rows) x 85 features (columns).
  • Udacity_CUSTOMERS_Subset.csv: Demographics data for customers of a mail-order company; 191652 persons (rows) x 85 features (columns).
  • Data_Dictionary.md: Detailed information file about the features in the provided datasets.
  • AZDIAS_Feature_Summary.csv: Summary of feature attributes for demographics data; 85 features (rows) x 4 columns

Each row of the demographics files represents a single person, but also includes information outside of individuals, including information about their household, building, and neighborhood. You will use this information to cluster the general population into groups with similar demographic properties. Then, you will see how the people in the customers dataset fit into those created clusters. The hope here is that certain clusters are over-represented in the customers data, as compared to the general population; those over-represented clusters will be assumed to be part of the core userbase. This information can then be used for further applications, such as targeting for a marketing campaign.

To start off with, load in the demographics data for the general population into a pandas DataFrame, and do the same for the feature attributes summary. Note for all of the .csv data files in this project: they're semicolon (;) delimited, so you'll need an additional argument in your read_csv() call to read in the data properly. Also, considering the size of the main dataset, it may take some time for it to load completely.

Once the dataset is loaded, it's recommended that you take a little bit of time just browsing the general structure of the dataset and feature summary file. You'll be getting deep into the innards of the cleaning in the first major step of the project, so gaining some general familiarity can help you get your bearings.

# Investigate patterns in the amount of missing data in each column.
azdias_ = azdias.fillna(-5) # filling -5 for all missing values for the ease of using it during groupby

def draw_missing_value_heatmap(df, feature_name, cmap):
    group = azdias_.groupby(feature_name).apply(lambda x: np.sum(x == -5)).drop(feature_name, axis = 1)
    df_heatmap = group.apply(lambda x: 100 * x/(x.sum()))
    df_heatmap = df_heatmap.loc[:,np.logical_not(df_heatmap.isnull().any())]
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15,4))
    ax = plt.gca()
    ax.set_title("Number of missing values for " + feature_name)
    sns.heatmap(df_heatmap,annot = False, linewidths=0.5, square = True, cmap = cmap)

# Remove the outlier columns from the dataset. (You'll perform other data
# engineering tasks such as re-encoding and imputation later.)
#Assuming the missing values in each feature should also fall under Gaussian distribution albeit one heavily skewed to the right. 
# 99.7% of all samples must be within  +/- 3(std deviation) from the mean else there are in the 0.03 percentile and could be 
# considered as outliers.

Std_num_missing_values = np.std(blanks_in_columns)
Avg_num_missing_values = np.mean(blanks_in_columns)

# lower_limit is not applicable as number of missing values in any feature can't go below zero.
lower_limit = Avg_num_missing_values - (3 * Std_num_missing_values) 
Upper_limit = Avg_num_missing_values + (3 * Std_num_missing_values)

outlier_index = blanks_in_columns[blanks_in_columns > Upper_limit].index
azdias.drop(labels = outlier_index, axis = 1, inplace=True)
print("The shape of the dataset after outlier columns are removed {}".format(azdias.shape))

azdias.drop("Type-of-building-R-C", axis = 1, inplace = True)

Discussion 1.1.2: Assess Missing Data in Each Column¶

Observations regarding missing data:¶

Note: All observations listed below has been gleaned from the heatmaps above. number "-5" in the heatmap means missing_unknown or naturally missing data. Also, i have converted all the columns names from German to English for the ease of my understanding. However in all discussion sections, i have presented my findings using German column names.

1) Women have more missing values than men. May be even in Germany, women socio-economic status is not on par with men yet or they take their privacy more seriously. 2) People those who are not part of any environmental sustainability movements in their youth tend to have more missing values. 3) High income earners tend to have more missing values. May be privacy is a big concern for these people, especially minimalistic high income earners. 4) German sounding names have more missing data. 5) If the length of residence is above 10 years they also seem to have more missing data. 6) People who lived in West germany tend to have more missing data. 7) People with middle level online affinity tend to have more missing values.

So, one assumption would be mostly high income earners tend to have more missing values when compared to other segments of the population. Also, they will have german sounding names and they would have mostly lived in the same residence for over 10 years as well as they would have lived in West Germany after world war and there infinity would be medium (code 2).

Columns removed¶

I simply assumed Gaussian distribution on number of missing data on each column. The columns that fell outside "mean + 3(std.dev)" i removed from the dataset as 99.7% of all data will fall within "mean +/- 3(std.dev)". Columns outside is in the 3rd percentile and can be considered outliers.

I have removed the following columns - 1) TITEL_KZ 2) AGER_TYP and 3) KK_KUNDENTYP

I have also dropped the column "GEBAEUDETYP", because in the customer dataset(Udacity_CUSTOMERS_Subset.csv), for this column "GEBAEUDETYP" we dont have any data point for subcategory "5: company building w/o known company" and it is creating one less column for customer dataset while using the clean_data function.

Step 1.1.3: Assess Missing Data in Each Row¶

Now, you'll perform a similar assessment for the rows of the dataset. How much data is missing in each row? As with the columns, you should see some groups of points that have a very different numbers of missing values. Divide the data into two subsets: one for data points that are above some threshold for missing values, and a second subset for points below that threshold.

In order to know what to do with the outlier rows, we should see if the distribution of data values on columns that are not missing data (or are missing very little data) are similar or different between the two groups. Select at least five of these columns and compare the distribution of values.

  • You can use seaborn's countplot() function to create a bar chart of code frequencies and matplotlib's subplot() function to put bar charts for the two subplots side by side.
  • To reduce repeated code, you might want to write a function that can perform this comparison, taking as one of its arguments a column to be compared.

Depending on what you observe in your comparison, this will have implications on how you approach your conclusions later in the analysis. If the distributions of non-missing features look similar between the data with many missing values and the data with few or no missing values, then we could argue that simply dropping those points from the analysis won't present a major issue. On the other hand, if the data with many missing values looks very different from the data with few or no missing values, then we should make a note on those data as special. Make sure you report your observations in the discussion section. Either way, you should continue your analysis below using just the subset of the data with few or no missing values.

Discussion 1.1.3: Assess Missing Data in Each Row¶

Observations: There are upto 51 missing values in a row. For some of the "number of NaNs in a row" the missing values seem to come from only particular columns and not randomnly from all columns. This indicates a pattern. For instance, when you look closely at 50 "NaN values in a row", this seems to come from one segment of people.

They all share these following characteristics.

1) They can be upto 60 years old 2) They are advertising-Enthusiast with restricted Cross-Channel 3) They are Nature fans 4) They are minimalistic high-income earners 5) They are incentive-receptive Normal-Returner 6) They are very high income earners 7) Their online affinity is in the middle level.

They are very high income category and tend to have lot of missing values when compared to other segment of people. Likewise, 46 "NaN values in a row" also belongs to very high income earners and have lot of missing values. Likewise most number of missing values seem to have unique characteristics of their own. We can even make a hypothesis that if a set of rows have a same number of missing values they are likely to have come from similar set of people(They could be clustered together) and we would be right atleast half of the time.

To seperate the dataset into two seperate subsets, i again assumed that number of NaNs in a row also would follow Gaussian distribution. Then, i placed all the rows that had number of NaNs less than or equal to "mean + (2 std.dev)" in subset 1 and rest in subset 2. In normal distribution 95.5% of all data must fall within "mean +/- (2 std.dev)".

Yes, both the subsets are qualitatively different as far code frequencies are concerned as can be seen from the countplots above. We can't drop the subset where there are many NaNs in the rows.

Step 1.2: Select and Re-Encode Features¶

Checking for missing data isn't the only way in which you can prepare a dataset for analysis. Since the unsupervised learning techniques to be used will only work on data that is encoded numerically, you need to make a few encoding changes or additional assumptions to be able to make progress. In addition, while almost all of the values in the dataset are encoded using numbers, not all of them represent numeric values. Check the third column of the feature summary (feat_info) for a summary of types of measurement.

  • For numeric and interval data, these features can be kept without changes.
  • Most of the variables in the dataset are ordinal in nature. While ordinal values may technically be non-linear in spacing, make the simplifying assumption that the ordinal variables can be treated as being interval in nature (that is, kept without any changes).
  • Special handling may be necessary for the remaining two variable types: categorical, and 'mixed'.

In the first two parts of this sub-step, you will perform an investigation of the categorical and mixed-type features and make a decision on each of them, whether you will keep, drop, or re-encode each. Then, in the last part, you will create a new data frame with only the selected and engineered columns.

Data wrangling is often the trickiest part of the data analysis process, and there's a lot of it to be done here. But stick with it: once you're done with this step, you'll be ready to get to the machine learning parts of the project!

Step 1.2.1: Re-Encode Categorical Features¶

For categorical data, you would ordinarily need to encode the levels as dummy variables. Depending on the number of categories, perform one of the following:

  • For binary (two-level) categoricals that take numeric values, you can keep them without needing to do anything.
  • There is one binary variable that takes on non-numeric values. For this one, you need to re-encode the values as numbers or create a dummy variable.
  • For multi-level categoricals (three or more values), you can choose to encode the values using multiple dummy variables (e.g. via OneHotEncoder), or (to keep things straightforward) just drop them from the analysis. As always, document your choices in the Discussion section.

def multi_level_or_binary_level(df, feature_name):
    if (len(df[feature_name].value_counts()) > 2):
        return 1
    return 0

Discussion 1.2.1: Re-Encode Categorical Features¶

Note: I have converted the German column names to English column names just for ease of understanding.

I decided to keep all the multi-level categorical columns as all of them have acceptable level of missing values as well as variance of its values is nowhere near zero. However i have decided to cast aside a binary level categorical variable, SOHO_KZ, as the variance of its values is near zero. In office-home-office-flag, little over 99% of all values fall in one category and the rest in another so it is unlikely to contribute much to our clustering.

There were two binary level categorical columns that had non-numeric values and i have mapped numeric values to them. Also, i didn't perform get_dummies on these columns.

However, all multi-level categorical columns were converted to string dtype and get_dummies applied over it.

Step 1.2.2: Engineer Mixed-Type Features¶

There are a handful of features that are marked as "mixed" in the feature summary that require special treatment in order to be included in the analysis. There are two in particular that deserve attention; the handling of the rest are up to your own choices:

  • "PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE" combines information on three dimensions: generation by decade, movement (mainstream vs. avantgarde), and nation (east vs. west). While there aren't enough levels to disentangle east from west, you should create two new variables to capture the other two dimensions: an interval-type variable for decade, and a binary variable for movement.
  • "CAMEO_INTL_2015" combines information on two axes: wealth and life stage. Break up the two-digit codes by their 'tens'-place and 'ones'-place digits into two new ordinal variables (which, for the purposes of this project, is equivalent to just treating them as their raw numeric values).
  • If you decide to keep or engineer new features around the other mixed-type features, make sure you note your steps in the Discussion section.

Be sure to check Data_Dictionary.md for the details needed to finish these tasks.

Discussion 1.2.2: Engineer Mixed-Type Features¶

I have re-engineered "PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE" and "CAMEO_INTL_2015" into two new features and dropped the original feature from the dataset.

Also, I have used "WOHNLAGE" to add one more feature to the dataset even as i keep the original feature alo. This new feature will tell whether the neighbourhood belongs to the urban or rural area.

Moreover, I have decided not to do anything with "LP_LEBENSPHASE_FEIN","LP_LEBENSPHASE_GROB","KBA05_BAUMAX" and "PLZ8_BAUMAX". Reason for my decision are as follows

When we consider "KBA05_BAUMAX" and "PLZ8_BAUMAX" they are mixed because they have two information 1) how many families reside in a bulding and 2) if the building is a microcell or a family home respectively. Even if we split them into two features, the housing type variable will have zero variability and that is highly unlikely to contribute anything to the task at hand.

When we consider "LP_LEBENSPHASE_FEIN", its sub-categories seem to give information for atleast 6 different variables like Martial status, Income level, Age, Homeownership, living with family, with or without children etc.., However none of the sub-categories all 6 potential variable information. Some subcategories have information for only one variable. For instance, "single independent persons" subcategory denotes that the person is single and "Independent persons" is at best ambiguous. This mixed variable can't be reliably split with the information we have. When we consider "LP_LEBENSPHASE_GROB", this subcategory is also afflicted with the same problem as "LP_LEBENSPHASE_FEIN", looks as if it has great potential but under delivers. Can't be reliably split. Also, these features violate rules of tidy data that each column should represent only one characteristic of the dataset. Moreover, given that the information contained in this feature is already present in other features, i have decided to drop both of them.

Step 1.2.3: Complete Feature Selection¶

In order to finish this step up, you need to make sure that your data frame now only has the columns that you want to keep. To summarize, the dataframe should consist of the following:

  • All numeric, interval, and ordinal type columns from the original dataset.
  • Binary categorical features (all numerically-encoded).
  • Engineered features from other multi-level categorical features and mixed features.

Make sure that for any new columns that you have engineered, that you've excluded the original columns from the final dataset. Otherwise, their values will interfere with the analysis later on the project. For example, you should not keep "PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE", since its values won't be useful for the algorithm: only the values derived from it in the engineered features you created should be retained. As a reminder, your data should only be from the subset with few or no missing values.

Step 1.3: Create a Cleaning Function¶

Even though you've finished cleaning up the general population demographics data, it's important to look ahead to the future and realize that you'll need to perform the same cleaning steps on the customer demographics data. def clean_data(df, feat_info, missing_or_unknown_lst):
    """
    Perform feature trimming, re-encoding, and engineering for demographics
    data

    INPUT: Demographics DataFrame
    OUTPUT: Trimmed and cleaned demographics DataFrame
    """

    # Put in code here to execute all main cleaning steps:
    # convert missing value codes into NaNs, ...
    dict_columns_missing_code = {i[0]: i[1] for i in zip(df.columns, missing_or_unknown_lst)}
    df.fillna(np.NaN, inplace=True)  # this line is redundant
    df[df.isin(dict_columns_missing_code)] = np.NaN
    blanks_in_columns = np.sum(df.isnull(), axis=0)

    # remove selected columns and rows, ...
    Std_num_missing_values = np.std(blanks_in_columns)
    Avg_num_missing_values = np.mean(blanks_in_columns)
    Upper_limit = Avg_num_missing_values + (3 * Std_num_missing_values)
    outlier_index = blanks_in_columns[blanks_in_columns > Upper_limit].index
    df.drop(labels=outlier_index, axis=1, inplace=True)
    
    if ((df.columns == "Academic-title-flag").any()):
        df.drop("Academic-title-flag", axis=1, inplace=True)

    if ((df.columns == "Best-ager-typology").any()):
        df.drop("Best-ager-typology", axis=1, inplace=True)

    if ((df.columns == "Consumer-pattern-past-12-months").any()):
        df.drop("Consumer-pattern-past-12-months", axis=1, inplace=True)
        
    if((df.columns == "Type-of-building-R-C").any()):
        df.drop("Type-of-building-R-C", axis=1, inplace=True)

    df["num_NaNs_in_row"] = np.sum(df.isnull(), axis=1)
    NaN_row_std_dev = np.std(df["num_NaNs_in_row"])
    NaN_row_mean = np.mean(df["num_NaNs_in_row"])
    NaN_row_threshold = NaN_row_mean + 2 * (NaN_row_std_dev)
    df["threshold_flag"] = df["num_NaNs_in_row"].apply(lambda x: 1 if x <= NaN_row_threshold else 2)
    df = df.loc[df["threshold_flag"] == 1, :]

    # select, re-encode, and engineer column values.
    categorical_present_index = feat_info.loc[feat_info["type"] == "categorical", :]["attribute_in_English"].isin(
        df.columns)
    categorical_necessary = feat_info.loc[feat_info["type"] == "categorical", :].loc[
        categorical_present_index, "attribute_in_English"]

    if ((df.columns == "Build-loc-EW-Germany").any()):
        df["Build-loc-EW-Germany"] = df["Build-loc-EW-Germany"].map({"W": 1, "O": 2})

    multi_level_features, binary_level_feature = [],[]
    categorical_necessary_list = [i for i in categorical_necessary]
    for i in categorical_necessary_list:
        return_value = multi_level_or_binary_level(df, i)
        if return_value == 1:
            multi_level_features.append(i)
        else:
            binary_level_feature.append(i)

    if ((df.columns == "small-office-home-office-flag").any()):
        df.drop("small-office-home-office-flag", axis=1, inplace=True)

    df = convert_column_dtypes_to_str(df, multi_level_features)

    dummies_multi_level = pd.get_dummies(df[multi_level_features], columns=multi_level_features)
    df.drop(multi_level_features, inplace=True, axis=1)
    df = pd.concat([df, dummies_multi_level], axis=1)
    del dummies_multi_level

    mixed_features = feat_info[feat_info["type"] == "mixed"]["attribute_in_English"]
    mixed_features_list = [i for i in mixed_features]
    azdias_less_NaNs = convert_column_to_float_dtype(df, mixed_features_list)

    if ((df.columns == "youth-dominating-movement").any()):
        df["youth-dominating-movement_decade"] = df["youth-dominating-movement"].map(
            {1: 1, 2: 1, 3: 2, 4: 2, 5: 3, 6: 3, 7: 3, 8: 4, 9: 4, 10: 5, 11: 5, 12: 5, 13: 5,14: 6, 15: 6})
        df["youth-dominating-movement_movement"] = df["youth-dominating-movement"].map(
            {1: 1, 3: 1, 5: 1, 8: 1, 10: 1, 12: 1, 14: 1, 2: 2, 4: 2, 6: 2, 7: 2, 9: 2, 11: 2,13: 2, 15: 2})
        df.drop("youth-dominating-movement", axis=1, inplace=True)

    if ((df.columns == "Welth-life-stage-intl-code").any()):
        df["Welth-life-stage-intl-code_ES"] = df["Welth-life-stage-intl-code"].apply(lambda x: (x - (x % 10)) / 10)
        df["Welth-life-stage-intl-code_LS"] = df["Welth-life-stage-intl-code"].apply(lambda x: x % 10)
        df.drop("Welth-life-stage-intl-code", axis=1, inplace=True)

    if ((df.columns == "Neighborhood-quality-rural-flag").any()):
        df["Neighborhood-quality-rural-urban"] = df["Neighborhood-quality-rural-flag"].map({0: 1, 1: 1, 2: 1, 3: 1, 4: 1, 5: 1, 7: 2, 8: 2})

    if ((df.columns == "Life-stage-fine-scale").any()):
        df.drop("Life-stage-fine-scale", axis=1, inplace=True)

    if ((df.columns == "Life-stage-rough-scale").any()):
        df.drop("Life-stage-rough-scale", axis=1, inplace=True)
        
    df.drop(["threshold_flag","num_NaNs_in_row"], axis = 1, inplace = True)

        # Return the cleaned dataframe.
    return df

Step 2.1: Apply Feature Scaling¶

Before we apply dimensionality reduction techniques to the data, we need to perform feature scaling so that the principal component vectors are not influenced by the natural differences in scale for features. Starting from this part of the project, you'll want to keep an eye on the API reference page for sklearn to help you navigate to all of the classes and functions that you'll need. In this substep, you'll need to check the following:

  • sklearn requires that data not have missing values in order for its estimators to work properly. So, before applying the scaler to your data, make sure that you've cleaned the DataFrame of the remaining missing values before applying your scaler. This can be as simple as just removing all data points with missing data, or applying an Imputer to replace all missing values. You might also try a more complicated procedure where you temporarily remove missing values in order to compute the scaling parameters before re-introducing those missing values and applying imputation. Think about how much missing data you have and what possible effects each approach might have on your analysis, and justify your decision in the discussion section below.
  • For the actual scaling function, a StandardScaler instance is suggested, scaling each feature to mean 0 and standard deviation 1.
  • For these classes, you can make use of the .fit_transform() method to both fit a procedure to the data as well as apply the transformation to the data at the same time. Don't forget to keep the fit sklearn objects handy, since you'll be applying them to the customer demographics data towards the end of the project.

Discussion 2.1: Apply Feature Scaling¶

Since my dataset has so many missing values simply droping all rows that have missing values would be droping too much valuable information. So i imputed the values using "median" strategy and then scaled it using standard scaler as suggested. The reason i have chosen "median" strategy is to avoid the effect of outliers as well as many features of our dataset is either categorical or ordinal so "mean" startegy would result in a decimal and it probably won't make much sense.

Based on what you find, select a value for the number of transformed features you'll retain for the clustering part of the project.
  • Once you've made a choice for the number of components to keep, make sure you re-fit a PCA instance to perform the decided-on transformation.

Discussion 2.2: Perform Dimensionality Reduction¶

I have decided to retain around 85% of variability so i have chosen 96 as my number of components as the acceptable variance explained in factor analysis for a construct to be valid is sixty per cent. The reason i have chosen to stop with around 85% variance is from here for every 2% additional variability we need to add 6 more features and the "curse of dimensionality" will be even more pronounced than what we have now.

Step 2.3: Interpret Principal Components¶

Now that we have our transformed principal components, it's a nice idea to check out the weight of each variable on the first few components to see if they can be interpreted in some fashion.

As a reminder, each principal component is a unit vector that points in the direction of highest variance (after accounting for the variance captured by earlier principal components). The further a weight is from zero, the more the principal component is in the direction of the corresponding feature. If two features have large weights of the same sign (both positive or both negative), then increases in one tend expect to be associated with increases in the other. To contrast, features with different signs can be expected to show a negative correlation: increases in one variable should result in a decrease in the other.

  • To investigate the features, you should map each weight to their corresponding feature name, then sort the features according to weight. The most interesting features for each principal component, then, will be those at the beginning and end of the sorted list. Use the data dictionary document to help you understand these most prominent features, their relationships, and what a positive or negative value on the principal component might indicate.
  • You should investigate and interpret feature associations from the first three principal components in this substep. To help facilitate this, you should write a function that you can call at any time to print the sorted list of feature weights, for the i-th principal component. This might come in handy in the next step of the project, when you interpret the tendencies of the discovered clusters.

    df_eigen_vector = pd.DataFrame(pca.components_[i], index=columns, columns=["eigen_vector"])
    print(df_eigen_vector.sort_values(by="eigen_vector", axis=0, ascending=False))
    return df_eigen_vector

Discussion 2.3: Interpret Principal Components¶

Each principal component seems to capture one characteristic. For instance, first prinicpal component seems to have strong positive correlation towards low income earners and their attributes. Quite expectedly, it has a strong negative correlation towards high income earners and their attributes. The most positive correlation is carried by the feature LP_STATUS_GROB_1 which denotes low-income earners.The second most positive correlation is carried by the feature PLZ8_ANTG3 which denotes 6-10 family houses in the PLZ8 region. Low income people tend to live in 6-10 family houses. In the other end, The second most negative correlation is carried by the feature KBA05_ANTG1 which denotes number of 1-2 family houses in the microcell an attribute of high income earners. So the more wealthy you are and associated attribute you carry you will have more negative correlation with the first principal component.

Second principal component : Characteristic this principal component is trying to explain is not so obvious and stark like the first and third principal component. But clear signs are there that this principal component is more concerned about personality traits than anything else. More carefree and sensual minded people SEMIO_LUST(persnlity-typo-sensual-minded) have a strong positive correlation and traits such as SEMIO_PFLICHT(persnlity-typo-dutiful),SEMIO_TRADV(persnlity-typo-tradional-minded),SEMIO_REL(persnlity-typo-religious). If we take this principal component a little far, we could say that liberal people will have a positive correlation and conservatives will have a negative correlation.

Third principal component: This component also clearly speaks about the personality type of the individual. As we can see pleasing personality traits such as SEMIO_VERT(persnlity-typo-dreamful), SEMIO_FAM(persnlity-typo-family-minded), SEMIO_SOZ(persnlity-typo-socially-minded), SEMIO_KULT(persnlity-typo-cultural-minded) have a very positive correlation with the third principal component whereas combative traits such as SEMIO_KAEM(persnlity-typo-combative attitude), SEMIO_DOM(persnlity-typo-dominant-minded), SEMIO_KRIT(persnlity-typo-critical-minded) has a strong negative correlation.

It can be gleaned that if we found a trait with a strong positive correlation among the eigen vectors it is highly likely that we will find the opposite of that particular trait with a strong negative correlation in the same principal component and we are clearly able to make sense of positive and negative correlation.

Step 3: Clustering¶

Step 3.1: Apply Clustering to General Population¶

You've assessed and cleaned the demographics data, then scaled and transformed them. Now, it's time to see how the data clusters in the principal components space. In this substep, you will apply k-means clustering to the dataset and use the average within-cluster distances from each point to their assigned cluster's centroid to decide on a number of clusters to keep.

  • Use sklearn's KMeans class to perform k-means clustering on the PCA-transformed data.
  • Then, compute the average difference from each point to its assigned cluster's center. Hint: The KMeans object's .score() method might be useful here, but note that in sklearn, scores tend to be defined so that larger is better. Try applying it to a small, toy dataset, or use an internet search to help your understanding.
  • Perform the above two steps for a number of different cluster counts. You can then see how the average distance decreases with an increasing number of clusters. However, each additional cluster provides a smaller net benefit. Use this fact to select a final number of clusters in which to group the data. Warning: because of the large size of the dataset, it can take a long time for the algorithm to resolve. The more clusters to fit, the longer the algorithm will take. You should test for cluster counts through at least 10 clusters to get the full picture, but you shouldn't need to test for a number of clusters above about 30.
  • Once you've selected a final number of clusters to use, re-fit a KMeans instance to perform the clustering operation. Make sure that you also obtain the cluster assignments for the general demographics data, since you'll be using them in the final Step 3.3.

def load_scores_centroids_checkpoint(filename):
    checkpoint = torch.load(filename)
    scores = checkpoint["scores"]
    centroids = checkpoint["centroids"]
    return centroids,scores

def get_model_score(data, n_cluster):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = n_cluster)
    model = kmeans.fit(data)
    scores = np.abs(model.score(data))
    #y_pred = model.predict(data)
    #sil_scores = silhouette_score(data, y_pred)
    return scores

def get_centroid_scores(data, num_clusters):
    list_clusters = list(range(2, num_clusters))
    scores = []
    #silhouette_scores = []
   
    for k in list_clusters:
        temp_score = get_model_score(data, k)
        if k % 5 == 0:
            print("cluster {} has passed successfully".format(k))
        scores.append(temp_score)
        #silhouette_scores.append(temp_sil_score)
    return scores, list_clusters

def plot_elbowchart(centroids, scores):
    fig = plt.figure(figsize = (16,9))
    ax1 = fig.add_subplot(111)
    ax1.plot(centroids, scores)
    ax1.set_xlabel("Number of clusters")
    ax1.set_ylabel("model score (lower is better)")
    ax1.set_title("Elbow method to find the number of clusters")
    ax1.set_xlim(min(centroids) - 1, max(centroids) + 1)
    #ax1.set_ylim(min(scores), max(scores))
    x_ticks = np.arange(min(centroids) - 1, max(centroids) + 1)
    ax1.set_xticks(x_ticks, minor=False)
    ax1.set_xticks(x_ticks, minor=True)
    y_ticks = np.arange(min(scores),max(scores), 500000)
    ax1.set_yticks(y_ticks, minor=False)
    ax1.set_yticks(y_ticks, minor=True)
    ax1.yaxis.grid(True, which="both")
    ax1.xaxis.grid(True, which="both")
    plt.show()

Step 3.3: Compare Customer Data to Demographics Data¶

At this point, you have clustered data based on demographics of the general population of Germany, and seen how the customer data for a mail-order sales company maps onto those demographic clusters. In this final substep, you will compare the two cluster distributions to see where the strongest customer base for the company is.

Consider the proportion of persons in each cluster for the general population, and the proportions for the customers. If we think the company's customer base to be universal, then the cluster assignment proportions should be fairly similar between the two. If there are only particular segments of the population that are interested in the company's products, then we should see a mismatch from one to the other. If there is a higher proportion of persons in a cluster for the customer data compared to the general population (e.g. 5% of persons are assigned to a cluster for the general population, but 15% of the customer data is closest to that cluster's centroid) then that suggests the people in that cluster to be a target audience for the company. On the other hand, the proportion of the data in a cluster being larger in the general population than the customer data (e.g. only 2% of customers closest to a population centroid that captures 6% of the data) suggests that group of persons to be outside of the target demographics.

Take a look at the following points in this step:

  • Compute the proportion of data points in each cluster for the general population and the customer data. Visualizations will be useful here: both for the individual dataset proportions, but also to visualize the ratios in cluster representation between groups. Seaborn's countplot() or barplot() function could be handy.
    • Recall the analysis you performed in step 1.1.3 of the project, where you separated out certain data points from the dataset if they had more than a specified threshold of missing values. If you found that this group was qualitatively different from the main bulk of the data, you should treat this as an additional data cluster in this analysis. Make sure that you account for the number of data points in this subset, for both the general population and customer datasets, when making your computations!
  • Which cluster or clusters are overrepresented in the customer dataset compared to the general population? Select at least one such cluster and infer what kind of people might be represented by that cluster. Use the principal component interpretations from step 2.3 or look at additional components to help you make this inference. Alternatively, you can use the .inverse_transform() method of the PCA and StandardScaler objects to transform centroids back to the original data space and interpret the retrieved values directly.
  • Perform a similar investigation for the underrepresented clusters. Which cluster or clusters are underrepresented in the customer dataset compared to the general population, and what kinds of people are typified by these clusters?
